ce:section.ce:para:
The CsSn0.5Pb0.5Br3@MTX-CS-FA nanoparticles exhibit three mechanisms that promote tumor cell damage (Fig. 1
                     ). First, under visible light illumination, the perovskite nanoparticles generate numerous electrons, facilitating the production of multiple ROS, including superoxide anions (O2
                     −), hydroxyl radicals (·OH), and singlet oxygen (1O2) [7,54]. Second, the photogenerated holes act as natural oxidants that deplete the GSH overexpressed in the cells, thereby inducing tumor cell apoptosis [54]. Finally, in the alkaline environment within tumor cells, these perovskite nanoparticles release the chemotherapeutic drug methotrexate (MTX) [61], which inhibits purine synthesis and simultaneously blocks the GCH1/BH4/DHFR system, leading to enhanced lipid peroxidation [62–64].
